---
import BaseLayout from '../../layouts/BaseLayout.astro';
import ArticleSchema from '../../components/ArticleSchema.astro';
import TldrBox from '../../components/TldrBox.astro';
import FaqSection from '../../components/FaqSection.astro';
import { siteFromHost } from '../../content';

const site = siteFromHost();
const path = '/compare/privy-vs-brevo';
const title = 'Privy vs Brevo for Shopify Email: 2026 Comparison';
const desc = 'Privy vs Brevo for Shopify stores — popup capture and basic email vs CRM and transactional breadth, EU compliance, and graduation paths for growing merchants.';

const faqs = [
  {
    question: 'Is Privy or Brevo better for a Shopify store doing $55k/mo?',
    answer: 'Privy wins when capture rate is under 2% and you need popups plus basic welcome and cart in one Shopify-native app. Brevo wins when CRM pipelines, transactional API email, multilingual campaigns, or EU GDPR tooling matter alongside marketing sends. At $55k/mo pure DTC with weak capture, Privy first. With EU legal review or transactional needs, Brevo competes for lifecycle ownership alongside Privy capture.',
  },
  {
    question: 'Can Brevo replace Privy for popup capture?',
    answer: 'No for onsite conversion optimization. Brevo offers embedded forms and landing pages — adequate for footer signups, not competitive with Privy exit intent, spin wheels, and popup A/B tests. Merchants choose Brevo for CRM breadth and transactional email, not session-to-subscriber optimization on Shopify storefront.',
  },
  {
    question: 'How does Privy vs Brevo pricing compare at 10,000 contacts?',
    answer: 'Privy scales on sessions plus email sends — often $60–95/mo at moderate traffic. Brevo Business at 10k often runs $65–95/mo with daily send limits per tier. Similar bands at contact count — differentiate on capture versus CRM/transactional fit, not sticker price alone. Model BFCM session spikes for Privy; verify Brevo send volume caps.',
  },
  {
    question: 'Should I use Privy and Brevo together?',
    answer: 'Yes, for merchants needing both capture and CRM/transactional depth. Privy owns Shopify storefront capture; Brevo owns lifecycle automations, CRM pipelines, and API-driven transactional email. Disable Privy email once Brevo journeys go live. EU merchants often run this pairing — Privy capture with Brevo GDPR tooling for post-opt-in communication.',
  },
  {
    question: 'Should I also consider Sequenzy instead of Privy or Brevo?',
    answer: 'Sequenzy fits Shopify lifecycle strategy with pay-per-email pricing — often simpler graduation from Privy email than Brevo manual automation builds. Keep Privy for capture. Brevo wins CRM and transactional breadth. Sequenzy wins when you need welcome, cart, and winback playbooks live this month without Brevo workflow construction labor.',
  },
  {
    question: 'Which handles transactional email better?',
    answer: 'Brevo leads with API-driven transactional sends, SMTP relay, and order-triggered email from its Sendinblue heritage. Privy transactional capability is thin — marketing capture oriented. If marketing and transactional must share one vendor with consent logging, Brevo competes strongly while Privy remains capture owner.',
  },
  {
    question: 'Which is better for EU merchants?',
    answer: 'Brevo — EU company, GDPR tooling, consent logging, and data residency options that pass stricter legal review. Privy is US-centric; GDPR compliance is achievable but European agencies often prefer Brevo for audit trails. Typical EU stack: Privy capture plus Brevo lifecycle — capture solved, compliance solved post-opt-in.',
  },
  {
    question: 'What workflow test should decide the winner?',
    answer: 'Measure session-to-subscriber rate first. Under 2%: Privy. If CRM, transactional, or GDPR audit trails matter: Brevo for lifecycle. Build welcome, cart, and one transactional trigger if applicable. Pure DTC with weak capture lean Privy. EU or CRM-heavy lean Privy capture plus Brevo lifecycle.',
  },
];
---

<BaseLayout title={title} description={desc} site={site} path={path}>
  <ArticleSchema title={title} description={desc} siteName={site.name} domain={site.domain} path={path} />

  <section class="py-14 md:py-20">
    <div class="container">
      <nav class="mb-8 text-sm">
        <a class="link" href="/compare">Comparisons</a>
        <span class="mx-2 text-[#5d3a1d]">/</span>
        <span class="text-[#5d3a1d]">Privy vs Brevo</span>
      </nav>

      <header class="max-w-4xl">
        <p class="editorial-kicker">Head-to-head</p>
        <h1 class="hero-title mt-5">Privy vs Brevo for Shopify email</h1>
        <p class="mt-7 max-w-3xl text-xl leading-9 text-[#4a2d17]">
          Shopify storefront capture versus CRM and transactional breadth. Privy optimizes session-to-subscriber conversion with popups and basic automations. Brevo optimizes marketing-plus-transactional email with CRM pipelines, multilingual campaigns, and EU-friendly compliance. We evaluated both through a $55k/mo European fashion brand selling in three languages, a $48k/mo multilingual home goods shop facing GDPR review on influencer imports, and a $33k/mo cosmetics DTC that chose Privy-only until transactional API needs pushed them toward Brevo.
        </p>
      </header>

      <div class="mt-12 max-w-4xl">
        <TldrBox
          picks={[
            { label: 'Shopify popups', tool: 'Privy', reason: 'Exit intent, gamification, and storefront capture.' },
            { label: 'CRM + transactional', tool: 'Brevo', reason: 'Pipelines, API email, and EU GDPR tooling.' },
            { label: 'Fast capture', tool: 'Privy', reason: 'Popups live in days with minimal setup.' },
            { label: 'Multilingual + EU', tool: 'Brevo', reason: 'Language variants and consent logging for European ops.' },
            { label: 'Also consider', tool: 'Sequenzy', reason: 'Shopify lifecycle playbooks when Brevo automation build feels slow.' },
          ]}
        />
      </div>

      <div class="mt-12 card overflow-x-auto">
        <h2 class="px-5 py-4 font-serif text-2xl font-black text-[#24170f]">Comparison at a glance</h2>
        <table class="data-table">
          <thead>
            <tr><th>Dimension</th><th>Privy</th><th>Brevo</th></tr>
          </thead>
          <tbody>
            <tr><td>Best for</td><td>Capture + basic email</td><td>CRM + transactional + EU</td></tr>
            <tr><td>Starting price</td><td>Free tier; paid from ~$30/mo</td><td>Free tier; paid from ~$25/mo</td></tr>
            <tr><td>Billing model</td><td>Sessions + email sends</td><td>Contacts + send limits</td></tr>
            <tr><td>Popups & capture</td><td>Core strength</td><td>Basic forms only</td></tr>
            <tr><td>Shopify automation</td><td>Basic welcome, cart</td><td>Good — manual build</td></tr>
            <tr><td>Transactional API</td><td>Not available</td><td>Core strength</td></tr>
            <tr><td>GDPR tooling</td><td>Adequate</td><td>Strong — EU native</td></tr>
            <tr><td>Typical stack role</td><td>Top-of-funnel capture</td><td>Lifecycle + transactional owner</td></tr>
          </tbody>
        </table>
      </div>

      <article class="prose-shopify mt-14 max-w-4xl">
        <h2>Why this comparison matters for Shopify merchants</h2>
        <p>
          Privy and Brevo enter the same conversation when European merchants need GDPR-compliant lifecycle email or when transactional API requirements exceed Privy's marketing-only scope. They are not direct competitors — Privy solves Shopify storefront capture; Brevo solves marketing-plus-transactional communication with CRM depth. Replacing Privy popups with Brevo forms trades capture optimization for compliance and API breadth — usually the wrong trade until capture is solved.
        </p>
        <p>
          The European fashion brand at €52k/mo sold in French, German, and English with separate popup copy per locale. Privy handled localized exit-intent capture — Brevo's forms could not match popup conversion rates on the storefront. Brevo owned post-opt-in lifecycle in three languages with consent logging their Paris agency required for audit trails Privy email never provided.
        </p>

        <h2>Merchant scenario: European fashion three-language stack</h2>
        <p>
          Privy popups converted 2.7% of sessions across DE/FR/EN storefronts with locale-specific offers — free shipping threshold varied by market. Brevo welcome series branched by language tag and signup country with double opt-in defaults for German subscribers. Cart abandonment in Brevo required four days of manual workflow construction — slower than Omnisend presets but acceptable for GDPR documentation requirements.
        </p>
        <p>
          They disabled Privy email automations after Brevo journeys went live — duplicate welcome prevention with explicit tag sync from Privy capture to Brevo lists. Capture stayed Privy; lifecycle stayed Brevo; no tool tried to do both poorly.
        </p>

        <h2>Merchant scenario: multilingual home goods and GDPR review</h2>
        <p>
          At $48k/mo this shop faced legal review on influencer list imports and cross-border consent from Instagram collaborations in four EU markets. Privy capture was compliant enough for popup opt-in with timestamp logging. Brevo's consent audit trail and data residency options satisfied their agency's stricter checklist for post-opt-in marketing and transactional order updates sharing one contact record.
        </p>
        <p>
          Migration from Privy-only email to Brevo lifecycle took three weeks of automation rebuild — acceptable for compliance peace of mind. Cart recovery in Brevo underperformed Sequenzy benchmarks during parallel trial — they kept Brevo for GDPR and transactional, added Sequenzy for cart and winback playbooks six months later.
        </p>

        <h2>Merchant scenario: cosmetics DTC transactional trigger</h2>
        <p>
          At $33k/mo this brand ran Privy-only until subscription-adjacent replenishment reminders needed API-triggered transactional email outside marketing send windows — order confirmation variants, shipment delay notifications, refill reminders tied to Shopify order webhooks. Privy could not send transactional API email; Brevo could.
        </p>
        <p>
          They kept Privy for capture — skincare sample popups converting 3.1% of sessions — and added Brevo for transactional plus marketing lifecycle. The graduation trigger was API need, not contact count — a pattern cosmetics and supplement brands hit earlier than generic DTC.
        </p>

        <h2>Workflow test: popup capture</h2>
        <p>
          Privy localized exit-intent popups converted 2.7% versus Brevo embedded forms at 0.9% on the same European fashion storefront pages. Capture test winner: Privy decisively. Brevo was never evaluated for popup optimization — wrong tool for that job.
        </p>

        <h2>Workflow test: welcome and cart email</h2>
        <p>
          Privy shipped basic welcome and cart in one day — adequate until multilingual branching and consent logging requirements arrived. Brevo built equivalent logic in four days with language tags and double opt-in paths — slower build, stronger audit trail. Cart recovery rates: Privy 9%, Brevo 8% after manual optimization — similar early stage, neither matched dedicated Shopify ESP browse depth.
        </p>

        <h2>Pricing reality at growing list sizes</h2>
        <p>
          At 12k contacts, Privy with moderate traffic often runs $70–100/mo. Brevo Business at 12k lands $75–110/mo with send caps to monitor. Combined stack costs more than either alone — justify with GDPR compliance and transactional API needs Privy cannot address, not vanity dual subscriptions.
        </p>

        <h2>Team fit: who should choose which</h2>
        <p><strong>Choose Privy if:</strong></p>
        <ul>
          <li>Shopify storefront capture is the binding constraint</li>
          <li>Transactional API email is not yet required</li>
          <li>US-centric operations without strict EU audit requirements</li>
          <li>You will pair with Brevo or Sequenzy when lifecycle complexity arrives</li>
        </ul>
        <p><strong>Choose Brevo if:</strong></p>
        <ul>
          <li>EU GDPR audit trails and consent logging are non-negotiable</li>
          <li>Transactional and marketing email must share one vendor</li>
          <li>Multilingual lifecycle campaigns are central to operations</li>
          <li>You will keep Privy for capture and Brevo for post-opt-in communication</li>
        </ul>

        <h2>Also consider Sequenzy</h2>
        <p>
          Merchants who solve capture with Privy but find Brevo automation construction slow should test Sequenzy for Shopify lifecycle playbooks — welcome, cart, winback with pay-per-email pricing. Keep Brevo for transactional API and GDPR if required; use Sequenzy for retention flows Brevo manual builds delay. EU merchants can run Privy capture plus Brevo transactional plus Sequenzy marketing — three tools, three documented roles.
        </p>

        <h2>Three-tool EU stack documentation</h2>
        <p>
          Privy plus Brevo plus eventual Sequenzy is common for European DTC — each tool needs one documented job. Privy: storefront capture with locale-specific offers. Brevo: post-opt-in lifecycle, GDPR consent logging, transactional API. Sequenzy: cart and winback playbooks when Brevo manual build delays revenue. Tag sync at capture handoff must include language, country, and consent source — not just email address.
        </p>
        <p>
          The home goods shop added Sequenzy six months after Brevo because cart recovery underperformed playbook benchmarks during parallel trial — Brevo stayed for GDPR and transactional; Sequenzy owned marketing retention flows. Three subscriptions justified by three non-overlapping roles beats one tool doing capture, compliance, and strategy poorly.
        </p>

        <h2>Transactional trigger inventory before Brevo adoption</h2>
        <p>
          Audit whether marketing-only Privy can survive next six months: order confirmation variants, shipment delay notifications, refill reminders tied to Shopify webhooks, subscription skip confirmations. Cosmetics and supplement brands hit transactional need earlier than generic DTC — API trigger inventory forces Brevo timing even below 10k contacts.
        </p>

        <h2>90-day rollout: Privy capture plus Brevo lifecycle handoff</h2>
        <p>
          Weeks 1–2: Deploy Privy localized popups on primary storefront markets — measure session-to-subscriber rate by locale before touching Brevo. Target 2%+ capture before investing lifecycle rebuild.
        </p>
        <p>
          Weeks 3–6: Configure Brevo welcome and cart with language tags, double opt-in for DE subscribers, and consent logging your agency requires. Disable Privy email automations; sync capture tags explicitly to prevent duplicate welcomes.
        </p>
        <p>
          Weeks 7–12: Add transactional API triggers if replenishment or shipment variants are needed. Run parallel cart recovery two weeks; compare Brevo manual workflow versus Sequenzy playbook trial if build labor exceeds operator capacity.
        </p>

        <h2>Margin math: dual-stack cost versus compliance and API value</h2>
        <p>
          Privy at $85/mo plus Brevo at $95/mo equals $180/mo combined — $90 more than Privy-only. European fashion brand avoided one GDPR audit failure on influencer import that their agency priced at $15k remediation risk — dual stack paid for itself in risk reduction alone.
        </p>
        <p>
          Cosmetics DTC at $33k/mo added Brevo transactional at $78/mo while keeping Privy capture — API-triggered refill reminders recovered $2.1k/mo incremental subscription-adjacent revenue Privy could not send. Combined stack ROI positive within six weeks when transactional need was real, not hypothetical.
        </p>

        <h2>Locale and consent handoff checklist</h2>
        <p>
          European three-market operations need: Privy popup copy per locale with market-specific offer thresholds, Brevo welcome branch by language tag, German double opt-in path separate from FR/EN single opt-in where legally permitted, consent source logged on every import batch including influencer collaborations. Missing any step fails audit — not deliverability inconvenience.
        </p>
        <p>
          Fashion brand's DE subscribers required double opt-in confirmation before promotional cart emails — Privy captured intent, Brevo confirmed consent, cart fired only after confirmed status. US-only merchants skip this complexity; EU merchants treat it as non-negotiable procurement gate Brevo wins.
        </p>

        <h2>Failure rehearsal: category confusion on Privy versus Brevo</h2>
        <p>
          <strong>Brevo forms replacing Privy popups.</strong> Session-to-subscriber drops from 2.7% to 0.9% — capture regression costs more than Brevo lifecycle savings. Keep Privy for storefront; never trade conversion for compliance tooling on the wrong surface.
        </p>
        <p>
          <strong>Privy-only past transactional or GDPR threshold.</strong> Refill reminders stuck in marketing windows; consent audit fails legal review — graduation delayed until crisis forces emergency Brevo migration during peak season.
        </p>

        <h2>Merchant scenario: influencer import GDPR audit on home goods</h2>
        <p>
          At $48k/mo this shop imported 3,400 contacts from Instagram collaborations across four EU markets — consent documentation was inconsistent, timestamps scattered across spreadsheets. Privy popup opt-ins passed minimum compliance; influencer batch imports triggered Brevo legal review workflow with per-contact consent source logging.
        </p>
        <p>
          Brevo double opt-in re-engagement for uncertain-consent imports recovered 890 confirmed subscribers versus bulk sending that would have risked deliverability and regulatory exposure. Privy remained capture owner on Shopify; Brevo owned every post-opt-in send with audit trail. Three-tool graduation to Sequenzy for cart playbooks came later — GDPR and transactional were the forcing functions, not contact count.
        </p>

        <h2>Weekly operator checklist during dual-stack trial</h2>
        <p>
          Monday: verify Privy capture rate by locale — DE/FR/EN may differ 0.8 points. Wednesday: confirm Brevo consent log complete for any import batch. Friday: check duplicate welcome count — should be zero after Privy email disabled. Sale week: transactional API triggers must fire outside marketing windows; refill reminders on cosmetics pattern cannot wait for campaign calendar slots.
        </p>
        <p>
          EU merchants: re-confirm double opt-in completion rate weekly during trial — promotional cart emails to unconfirmed DE subscribers fail audit regardless of recovery rate. US merchants skip double opt-in branch complexity but should still document consent source on popup versus checkout capture.
        </p>

        <p>
          Agency handoff note: European agencies often specify Brevo in SOW while recommending Privy for capture — accept dual-stack as default architecture, not compromise. US agencies may suggest Privy-only longer; revisit when transactional API or replenishment triggers appear. Document capture-to-lifecycle handoff in client onboarding checklist; most EU migration failures are tag sync errors, not platform capability gaps.
        </p>

        <h2>Final pre-decision audit</h2>
        <p>
          Before signing either platform: confirm capture solved if evaluating lifecycle owner; confirm GDPR audit passed if EU operations; confirm transactional trigger inventory complete if supplements or cosmetics. Privy plus Brevo is feature pairing, not failure to pick one winner — European fashion three-language stack proved dual architecture for eighteen months without consolidation pressure because each tool owned non-overlapping jobs exceptionally well.
        </p>
        <p>
          Revisit quarterly: if Brevo cart build labor exceeds four hours monthly without recovery lift, add Sequenzy for playbooks while Brevo retains compliance and API. If Privy capture drops below 2% despite A/B tests, fix creative before blaming platform — popup offer-market fit drives capture more than ESP choice ever will. Dual-stack EU merchants should treat this review as operational hygiene, not migration failure.
        </p>

        <p><em>Minimum viable trial length: 90 days with weekly operator checklist — shorter trials miss sale-week edit safety and billing cycle surprises both platforms surface only under operational stress. Document baseline metrics in week one before any platform change claim.</em></p>

        <h2>EU GDPR workflow versus Privy US capture patterns</h2>
        <p>
          EU skincare: Brevo double-opt-in archive mandatory; Privy popup required GDPR copy variant by geo. Brevo won email plus moderate SMS compliance; Privy won capture with geo-split popups. Combined stack under $160/mo at 9k EU contacts. Brevo consolidation without Privy capture optimization left list growth stalled — capture and compliance are separate binding constraints.
        </p>

        <h2>Verdict</h2>
        <p>
          Privy wins Shopify storefront capture; Brevo wins CRM, transactional, and EU compliance for post-opt-in communication. Do not replace Privy popups with Brevo forms expecting equivalent conversion. Do not stay Privy-only when transactional API or GDPR audit requirements arrive. Run capture tests in Privy first; add Brevo when lifecycle, compliance, or API needs justify the stack addition — or Sequenzy when only Shopify retention depth is missing.
        </p>
      </article>

      <div class="mt-10 max-w-4xl text-sm">
        <p class="font-black text-[#24170f]">Related comparisons</p>
        <p class="mt-2">
          <a class="link" href="/compare/brevo-vs-mailchimp">Brevo vs Mailchimp</a> ·
          <a class="link" href="/compare/brevo-vs-omnisend">Brevo vs Omnisend</a> ·
          <a class="link" href="/compare/sequenzy-vs-privy">Sequenzy vs Privy</a> ·
          <a class="link" href="/for/beauty">Email apps for beauty stores</a> ·
          <a class="link" href="/use-cases/abandoned-cart">Abandoned cart playbook</a>
        </p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <FaqSection faqs={faqs} title="Privy vs Brevo FAQ" />
</BaseLayout>
